Forensics Evidence Collection > [T2]: Windows Memory Dead Acquisition

Now that we have discussed live windows systems, what about powered-off (also known as dead) windows systems?

As explained earlier, the RAM does not store data permanently and clears its content at each reboot! Ideally, memory acquisition should be performed on a live machine. However, as a forensic analyst, you may arrive at the investigation scene and discover that a system admin powered off the computer for various reasons (e.g., stopping ransomware from encrypting disk content).

Fortunately, the way Windows systems work resulted in producing some disk files that can help you retrieve some or all of the memory content even after the computer is turned off, such as:

 

  • Hibernation file (hiberfil.sys): Windows systems, especially laptops, has a power-saving option called hibernation. When the computer is put into hibernation mode (by selecting hibernate from the start menu), the system will create a hidden file named "hiberfil.sys" located at the drive's root folder where the operating system is installed (i.e., C:\).

    Example hiberfil.sys and pagefile.sys files location and size


    This file contains a replica of memory content when the machine was put into hibernation and is used to restore the user session when the system boots up. The file size is approximately equal to the RAM size assigned to the system and serves as a memory image ready for analysis.
     
  • Paging file (pagefile.sys): this file is part of a memory-management scheme Windows uses to store parts from memory on your local hard drive. It's used to virtually extend available system memory by allowing the OS to move infrequently accessed memory content from physical memory (RAM) to the page file on the disk resulting in better performance.

    This pagefile.sys file offers you an opportunity to retrieve parts of the memory content that may be helpful to the investigation. Like hiberfil.sys, it's located at the drive's root folder where the operating system is installed (i.e., C:\).

  • CrashDumps:
    Do you remember those blue screens of death (BSOD) you see when Windows crashes?


    A memory/crash/core dump is a .dmp file created by the OS at 'C:\Windows\MEMORY.DMP' containing the recorded state of the computer memory at the time of the crash. This is a very good resource explaining crash dumps in detail.

    The bottom line, live memory acquisition is ideal but will not always be possible. When you arrive at the investigation scene, you should first acquire a live memory image and clone the above disk files containing parts of the computer memory content.
